 businesses involved in the R502 refrigerant market. Mexico's large automotive sector, combined with its significant industrial and commercial refrigeration requirements, means that there is still a demand for maintenance, repairs, and refrigerant refills in systems that are not yet transitioned to newer alternatives. This provides continued market activity for R502, even as newer refrigerants gain ground. Furthermore, the ongoing growth of the food and beverage sector, along with Mexico's industrial manufacturing capabilities, creates a steady demand for refrigeration solutions. Even with the ongoing phase-out of R502, opportunities exist for companies providing cost-effective and regulatory-compliant refrigerant replacements. Additionally, the focus on energy-efficient and sustainable refrigeration systems provides avenues for innovation and new product development. Companies offering eco-friendly refrigerants that align with Mexico’s evolving environmental goals are well-positioned to capture market share, even as R502’s role continues to diminish in the long term. <h2>Frequently Asked Questions</h2> <p><strong>1. What is R502 refrigerant?</strong><br>R502 is a refrigerant blend of R22 and R115, historically used in refrigeration systems for medium and low-temperature applications.</p> <p><strong>2. Is R502 still used in Mexico?</strong><br>Yes, R502 is still in use in certain legacy refrigeration systems, especially in older automotive, commercial, and industrial refrigeration units.</p> <p><strong>3. Why is R502 being phased out?</strong><br>R502 is being phased out due to its high ozone depletion potential and global warming potential, in line with international environmental regulations.</p> <p><strong>4. What are the alternatives to R502?</strong><br>Alternatives to R502 include R404A, R407C, and R134A, which have lower environmental impact and better energy efficiency.</p> <p><strong>5. Can R502 be replaced in existing systems?</strong><br>Yes, R502 can be 